T1  - Reciprocity in Dynamic Employment Relationships
AU  - Fahn, Matthias
Y1  - 2023/01/10
PY  - 2023
DA  - 2023/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2022.4657
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2022.4657
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 5816
EP  - 5829
VL  - 69
IS  - 10
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This paper analyzes a dynamic relational contract for employees with reciprocal preferences. A model of a long-term employment relationship is developed that implies that generous upfront wages activate the norm of reciprocity and then are more important when an employee is close to retirement. In earlier stages, direct incentives promising a bonus in exchange for effort are more effective. Hence, direct and reciprocity-based incentives reinforce each other and should be used in combination. Moreover, a more competitive labor market may increase the utilization of reciprocity-based incentives.This paper was accepted by Axel Ockenfels, behavioral economics and decision analysis.Funding: This work was supported by Hardegg?sche Stiftung, the Deutsche Forschungsgemeinschaft [CRC TRR 190], and the Austrian Science Fund [Grant P 33307-G].Supplemental Material: The online appendices are available at https://doi.org/10.1287/mnsc.2022.4657.
AB  - This paper analyzes a dynamic relational contract for employees with reciprocal preferences. A model of a long-term employment relationship is developed that implies that generous upfront wages activate the norm of reciprocity and then are more important when an employee is close to retirement. In earlier stages, direct incentives promising a bonus in exchange for effort are more effective. Hence, direct and reciprocity-based incentives reinforce each other and should be used in combination. Moreover, a more competitive labor market may increase the utilization of reciprocity-based incentives.This paper was accepted by Axel Ockenfels, behavioral economics and decision analysis.Funding: This work was supported by Hardegg?sche Stiftung, the Deutsche Forschungsgemeinschaft [CRC TRR 190], and the Austrian Science Fund [Grant P 33307-G].Supplemental Material: The online appendices are available at https://doi.org/10.1287/mnsc.2022.4657.
